full_text: Observe how the contact information is updated for a future dated change on the policy. First, create a new person account for Jane Smith. Go to the Contacts page. Edit the contact. Update the contact to reflect that she is single and born on April 1, 1987. Create a new personal auto submission. Go to the Contacts page. Go to Drivers. Add Jane as the only driver. Enter Required fields. Go to Vehicles. Add a Vehicle. Quote the submission. Issue Policy. Go to the Policy File.  After a while, Jane calls to inform that she is getting married in a week and would like to add her husband John Doe as a driver on her policy. Start a Policy Change Transaction. Enter an effective date as two months after the policy's start date.  Enter a description. Enter a description. Click Next. Go to Drivers. Add a new driver for John Doe. Fill in the details as required and save the new driver. Click the row for Jane Smith. Jane would also like to change her last name to John Doe. Change her status to Married. Quote the Policy Change. Issue Policy. Go to the Account. On the Account, what is the last name of Jane? Why? The last name of Jane is Smith. Future dated contact data changes at the policy level do not flow back up to the account, because the contact at the account level is considered the current data and cannot be future dated. Press Alt plus Shift plus T. Navigate to Internal Tools. Select Testing System Clock. Set the clock to the effective date of the policy change job. Click Change Date. Go to Server Tools. Select Batch Process Info. Run the Batch Process Supply Pending Account Data Updates. In the top right corner of the window, click the Options menu. Click Return to Policy Center. Go to Jane's account. After advancing the system clock to the policy changes effective date and running the batch process, what is the last name of Jane on the account? Why? The last name of Jane is Doe. Because the batch process supply pending account data updates automatically updates the account contact data from the policy changes on the job effective date. Go to the Policy File. Now let's look at a backdated change of the contact information on the policy. After three months, Jane calls to inform that the birth year on her policy is wrong and needs to be corrected to 1985. Start a new policy change. This change should take effect from the beginning of the policy. It is a backdated change so you will get a warning about an out-of-sequence transaction. Click OK to continue. Go to Drivers. Change Jane's birth year to 1985. Click Quote. Issue Policy. Go to the Account. Go to Contacts. The backdated changes do not flow back up to the account. The contact birthdate is not updated in the account file. Activities are created on the account. The activities inform the user about the contact changes that may need to be updated on the account. Go to the Notes page. Notes are created for the contact changes as well. This is the end of the demonstration for future dated and backdated policy changes. The !

Update the contact to reflect that she is single and born on April 1, 1987. Create a new personal auto submission.
Go to the Contacts page. Go to Drivers. Add Jane as the only driver. Enter Required fields. Go to Vehicles. Add a Vehicle. Quote the submission.
Issue Policy. Go to the Policy File.
After a while, Jane calls to inform that she is getting married in a week and would like to add her husband John Doe as a driver on her policy. Start a Policy Change Transaction.
Enter an effective date as two months after the policy's start date.

Enter a description.
Click Next.
Go to Drivers.
Add a new driver for John Doe.
Fill in the details as required and save the new driver. Click the row for Jane Smith.
Jane would also like to change her last name to John Doe.
Change her status to Married. Quote the Policy Change.
Issue Policy.
Go to the Account.
On the Account, what is the last name of Jane? Why? The last name of Jane is Smith.
Future dated contact data changes at the policy level do not flow back up to the account, because the contact at the account level is considered the current data and cannot be future dated.
Press Alt plus Shift plus T.
Navigate to Internal Tools.
Select Testing System Clock.
Set the clock to the effective date of the policy change job.
Click Change Date.
Go to Server Tools.
Select Batch Process Info.
Run the Batch Process Supply Pending Account Data Updates.
In the top right corner of the window, click the Options menu.
Click Return to Policy Center.
Go to Jane's account.
After advancing the system clock to the policy changes effective date and running the batch process, what is the last name of Jane on the account? Why?
The last name of Jane is Doe.
Because the batch process supply pending account data updates automatically updates the account contact data from the policy changes on the job effective date.
Go to the Policy File.
Now let's look at a backdated change of the contact information on the policy.
After three months, Jane calls to inform that the birth year on her policy is wrong and needs to be corrected to 1985.
Start a new policy change.
This change should take effect from the beginning of the policy.
It is a backdated change so you will get a warning about an out-of-sequence transaction.
Click OK to continue.
Go to Drivers.
Change Jane's birth year to 1985.
Click Quote.
Issue Policy.
Go to the Account.
Go to Contacts.
The backdated changes do not flow back up to the account.
The contact birthdate is not updated in the account file.
Activities are created on the account.
The activities inform the user about the contact changes that may need to be updated on the account.
Go to the Notes page.
Notes are created for the contact changes as well.
This is the end of the demonstration for future dated and backdated policy changes.
